# GoldenLayout: mirror the whole `dist` directory as a single opaque
# entity.  `third_party/golden-layout/dist` is a POSIX symlink into
# `node_modules/golden-layout/dist` — on Linux a /nix/store path, on
# Windows a real NTFS directory junction that env.ps1's
# `Ensure-GoldenLayoutAsset` installs (the bare Windows checkout
# materializes the symlink as a 40-byte text stub, which the activation
# script replaces with a junction so the build can traverse it).
#
# Why this is a whole-directory `!tup_preserve` rule rather than a
# per-file `foreach`/glob: Tup's parser-stage directory-ID lookup does
# NOT traverse symlinks whose targets escape the tup-managed tree
# (here, into `/nix/store`).  Any rule whose source path has components
# *inside* the symlinked directory — `dist/css/*.css`,
# `dist/css/goldenlayout-base.css`, etc. — fails parsing with
# `Failed to find directory ID for dir '...'`.  This is exactly how
# the sibling rules for `third_party/monaco-editor/min`,
# `third_party/@exuanbo`, `third_party/mousetrap`, etc. work: they
# name the symlinked subdirectory itself as the input and let Tup
# treat it as a single leaf, never enumerating inside it.
#
# `!tup_preserve` on the whole `dist` symlink produces a corresponding
# symlink at `build-debug/public/third_party/golden-layout/dist` that
# points back into the source tree, so the runtime `<link>` references
# in `frontend/index.html` and `frontend/server_index.ejs` resolve to
# the real GoldenLayout stylesheets on every platform.
: third_party/golden-layout/dist |> !tup_preserve |> %f
: third_party/mousetrap |> !tup_preserve |> %f
: third_party/vex-js |> !tup_preserve |> %f
: third_party/xterm |> !tup_preserve |> %f
: foreach dist/* |> !tup_preserve |> %f
